<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0136</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Compulsory Purchase Association – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This document is submitted on behalf of the Compulsory Purchase Association.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.67pt; padding-left:3.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It seems to provide for the removal by the Deregulation Bill of an unnecessary step in the vesting of land contained in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Schedule 1 of the Compulsory Purchase (Vesting Declarations) Act 1981.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposal is to bring the vesting process in line with other compulsory purchase processes by removing a step that can delay vesting(and therefore is a delaying factor for infrastructure projects) and which offers a degree of protection for landowners out of proportion to its benefit and purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction – The CPA</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This document is submitted to the Committee considering the Deregulation Bill on behalf of the Compulsory Purchase Association (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CPA</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">). </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Association’s objective is to work for the public benefit in relation to compulsory purchase and compensation in all its forms. This includes promoting the highest professional standards amongst practitioners at all levels and participating in debate as to matters of current interest in compulsory purchase and compensation. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The CPA has some 500 members practising in this field, including surveyors, lawyers, accountants, planners and officers of public authorities.   This consultation response has been formulated following discussions within the National Committee of the CPA.  </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The CPA has reviewed the Deregulation Bill and the call for evidence and has no specific comment on the Bill's content.  It believes that the proposal below would meet the purposes of the long title of the Bill, namely to reduce the burdens resulting from legislation for businesses and other organisations; and to  make provision for the repeal of legislation which no longer has practical use.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Material detriment on vested land</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Where an acquiring authority exercise powers by service of Notice to Treat and Notice of Entry and seeks to acquire only part of an interest, Section 8 of the Compulsory Purchase Act 1965 gives the right for the Tribunal to require the acquiring authority to purchase the whole if part cannot be taken without material detriment to the remainder. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The 1965 Act provides that the claimant can serve notice under Section 8 requiring the acquiring authority to acquire the entirety of the interest. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There is no prescribed process but the acquiring authority can still take possession of the land in question and commence the scheme works.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If the acquiring authority instead chooses to acquire land by the "modern" proves of a vesting declaration under the Compulsory Purchase (Vesting declarations) Act 1981, a different process applies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Paragraph 3 of Schedule 1 of the Compulsory Purchase (Vesting Declarations) Act 1981 dis-applies S8 and specifies a procedure. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Where Notice of the Intention to make a GVD is served in respect of less than the entire interest held by a claimant, if the claimant believes that it will suffer material detriment through only the part of its interest being acquired, the Act provides that the Claimant is entitled to serve a ‘notice of objection to severance’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.7</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The notice of objection seeks to have the entirety of the claimant’s interest acquired instead of just the part of the interest that the acquiring authority has identified in its Notice of Intention. This notice has to be served within 21 days of the Notice of Intention, in accordance with Para 2 (1) of Schedule 1 of the Act. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.8</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The key problem is the land proposed to be severed does not vest nor can possession be taken until material detriment is determined by the Lands Chamber of the Upper Tribunal or accepted by the acquiring authority. This can have serious consequences in terms of both cost and the timing of the delivery of the scheme.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.9</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> At the present time, and traditionally, a reference to the Lands Chamber could take a well over a year before a hearing to determine the issue is held and a decision given. In consequence, delivery of the scheme can be delayed for a year or more and that delay almost invariably results in a substantial increase in cost for the scheme under construction.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.10</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This programme risk makes the vesting of part of an interest an unacceptable risk to acquiring authorities unless they are prepared to acquire the whole of the relevant land at the outset. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.11</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The service of a notice of objection to severance should not prevent either the vesting of title to the land in question that is required for the scheme in the acquiring authority (or possession being taken of that interest in land by the authority so as to enable the scheme works to continue). However in the event of the claimant and the acquiring authority not being able to reach agreement as to whether or not the entirety of the interest in question should be acquired, the claimant should still have the right to refer the dispute to the Lands Chamber for determination of whether the whole of their interest should be taken in exactly the same way that Section 8 of the CPA 1965 operates.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.12</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposal is that the GVD Schedule 1 process should be brought into line with the CPA 1965 Section 8 approach by repealing paragraph 3 of Schedule1 to the 1981 Act (which says land does not vest nor can possession be taken until material detriment determined by the Tribunal or accepted by the acquiring authority.) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.13</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Minor consequential amendments to the remainder of Schedule 1 are required. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.14</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposal would mean the claimant would therefore be in exactly the same position following vesting as with notice to treat/entry in so far as the timing of determination of material detriment. The claimant will suffer no disadvantage by this proposed reform whilst the project will be able to proceed as planned, and as intended by Parliament on the granting of compulsory purchase powers for the scheme in question.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Proposed Drafting:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">[ ] Compulsory purchase of land – divided land</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Compulsory Purchase (Vesting Declarations) Act 1981 is amended as follows.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In Paragraph 3 of Schedule 1 is deleted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Paragraph 4 (1) of Schedule 1 is deleted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Paragraph 5 of Schedule 1 is deleted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Words "or Paragraph 5" are deleted from Paragraph 6.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">16 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6pt">1</span></p></div></body></html>